TSMC Earnings
-------------

From Bloomberg ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-04-18/tsmc-po=
sts-first-profit-growth-in-a-year-after-global-ai-boom ) last month:

Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Co. scaled back its outlook for a chip m=
arket expansion, cautioning that the smartphone and personal-computing mark=
ets remain weak. The world=E2=80=99s largest maker of advanced chips cut it=
s expectations for 2024 semiconductor market growth =E2=80=94 excluding mem=
ory chips =E2=80=94 to about 10%, from above that figure. Chief Executive O=
fficer C. C. Wei also trimmed his growth forecast for the foundry sector, w=
hich TSMC leads. Meanwhile, the company maintained its estimates for spendi=
ng at anywhere between $28 billion and $32 billion amid capacity expansion =
and upgrades this year. =E2=80=9CMacroeconomic and geopolitical uncertainty=
 persists, potentially weighing on consumer sentiment and end-market demand=
,=E2=80=9D Wei told analysts on a conference call. TSMC=E2=80=99s stock sli=
d more than 6% in Taipei, the biggest intraday decline in about 18 months.

The outlook overshadowed what was otherwise a solid beat on projected reven=
ue that reaffirmed the growth TSMC and other chipmakers are seeing from dem=
and for all things artificial intelligence. The new forecast also highlight=
s the diverging fortunes of those who make chips for consumer products and =
those who are designing and manufacturing the most advanced chips for AI pr=
ocessing.

This was a quarter where Taiwan itself had a big impact on margins. First, =
the earthquake; CFO Wendell Huang said in his prepared remarks on the earni=
ngs call ( https://investor.tsmc.com/chinese/encrypt/files/encrypt_file/rep=
orts/2024-04/34ff75e23e53246302ce3a8d90d0423c57c6b120/TSMC%201Q24%20Transcr=
ipt.pdf ) :

I will start by making some comments on the impact from the April 3 earthqu=
ake. On April 3, an earthquake of 7.2 magnitude struck Taiwan, and the maxi=
mum magnitude of our fabs was 5. Safety systems and protocols at our fabs w=
ere initiated immediately, and all TSMC personnel are safe. Based on TSMC=
=E2=80=99s deep experience and capabilities in earthquake response and dama=
ge prevention as well as regular disasters drills, the overall tool recover=
y in our fabs reached more than 70% within the first 10 hours and were full=
y recovered by the end of the third day. There were no power outages, no st=
ructural damage to our fabs, and there=E2=80=99s no damage to our critical =
tools, including all of our EUV lithography tools. That being said, a certa=
in number of wafers in process were impacted and had to be scrapped, but we=
 expect most of the lost production to be recovered in the second quarter a=
nd, thus, minimum impact to our second quarter revenue. We expect the total=
 impact from the earthquake to reduce our second quarter gross margin by ab=
out 50 basis points, mainly due to the losses associated with wafer scraps =
and material loss.

Full recovery within 3 days is remarkable. Previously on Sharp Tech ( https=
://sharptech.fm/member/episode/amazon-and-the-just-walk-out-parable-mythbus=
ting-on-meta-and-tsmc-the-xz-backdoor-and-its-implications ) I told the sto=
ry of TSMC=E2=80=99s struggles in recovering from a major earthquake in 199=
9; full recovery took months (and, as I explained on that episode, was a bi=
g factor in TSMC growing much closer to ASML). I do suspect that that 1999 =
earthquake was significantly stronger for TSMC=E2=80=99s fabs, though, give=
n that its epicenter was closer than the earthquake last month.

Second is energy; again from Huang:

After last year=E2=80=99s 17% electricity price increase from April 1, TSMC=
=E2=80=99s electricity price in Taiwan has increased by another 25% startin=
g April 1 this year. This is expected to take out 70 to 80 basis points fro=
m our second quarter gross margin. Looking ahead to the second half of the =
year, we expect the impact from higher electricity cost to continue and dil=
ute our gross margin by 60 to 70 basis points. We also expect the higher el=
ectricity cost to indirectly lead to higher materials, chemical and gases a=
nd other variable costs.

The electricity situation in Taiwan is pretty dysfunctional: most power com=
es from imported coal and natural gas, which jumped up in price after Russi=
a=E2=80=99s invasion of Ukraine. That of course happened two years ago, but=
 all of Taiwan=E2=80=99s power is delivered by a state-managed utility, whi=
ch is politically constrained from raising prices; moreover, when it does f=
inally get permission to raise prices (by losing $6.2 billion last year, an=
d even more the year before that =E2=80=94 and a slightly lesser amount thi=
s year), almost all of the price raises go to industrial users; residential=
 users are only seeing price raises of between 3% and 10%.

Imported energy, meanwhile, is obviously vulnerable to a blockade in the ev=
ent of a confrontation with China, which makes it particularly bizarre that=
 the country remains determined to wind down its nuclear power plants; the =
plan is to make up the difference with off shore wind energy, but the proje=
ct is ballooning in costs and way behind schedule.

And yet, despite all the dysfunction, TSMC still finds it much cheaper to m=
ake chips in Taiwan; that=E2=80=99s why, as I have noted previously, the co=
mpany will be charging more for chips made abroad. From CEO C.C. Wei=E2=80=
=99s prepared remarks:

In today=E2=80=99s fragmented globalization environment, cost will be highe=
r for everyone, including TSMC, our customers, our competitors and the enti=
re semiconductor industry. We plan to manage and minimize the overseas cost=
 gap by, first, pricing strategically to reflect the value of geographic fl=
exibility; second, working closely with government to secure their support;=
 and third, leveraging our fundamental advantage of manufacturing technolog=
y leadership and our large-scale manufacturing base, which no other manufac=
turer in this industry can match.

Thus, even after factoring in the higher cost of overseas fab, we are confi=
dent to deliver a long-term gross margin of 53% and higher and sustainable =
ROE of greater than 25% that we have committed to our shareholders. At the =
same time, TSMC will be the most efficient and cost-effective manufacturer =
in the region that we operate. We are continuing to provide our customers w=
ith the most advanced technology at scale to support their growth.

Those overseas fabs, meanwhile, and contrary to a lot of media reports, con=
tinue to be on track; Wei said:

In Arizona, we have received the strong commitment and support from our U.S=
. customers and plan to build 3 fabs, which help to create greater economie=
s of scale. Each of our fab in Arizona will have a clean-room area that is =
approximately double the size of a typical logic fab. We have made signific=
ant progress in our first fab, which has already entered engineering wafer =
production in April with the N4 process technology. We are well on track fo=
r volume production in first half 2025.

This raises another question, though.

TSMC=E2=80=99s Pricing Mistake
----------------------

From Tom=E2=80=99s Hardware ( https://www.tomshardware.com/tech-industry/se=
miconductors/rumors-swirl-that-tsmc-chairman-mark-liu-was-forced-to-retire-=
over-arizona-fab-debacle ) last December:

On December 19, TSMC announced the retirement of chairman Mark Liu, but the=
re has been increasing speculation that the chairman=E2=80=99s five-year te=
nure might have been ended forcibly (via Wealth Magazine). Taiwanese media =
voices theorize that Liu=E2=80=99s abrupt departure from the company is rel=
ated to the construction delays for TSMC=E2=80=99s Arizona fab, which Liu s=
pent much of 2023 trying to keep on track.

Retirement isn=E2=80=99t unusual for someone who=E2=80=99s been working for=
 roughly forty years, but there are two main reasons why Liu=E2=80=99s reti=
rement has stirred up speculation. The first is that it was very sudden; th=
ere was very little warning at all. Additionally, the press release surroun=
ding his retirement came from TSMC and not Liu himself. By contrast, TSMC f=
ounder Morris Chang, who served as both chairman and CEO, announced his own=
 retirement in 2018 and made his own statements.

According to industry rumors, the immediate cause for Liu=E2=80=99s removal=
 was problems surrounding Fab 21. The construction for Fab 21 in Arizona ha=
s been troubled since it began in April 2021, and chairman Liu blamed local=
 Arizonan workers for the delays. His solution to get Fab 21 back on track =
was to send experienced TSMC workers from Taiwan, but this only angered the=
 locals and unions. Eventually, the chairman backtracked on his comments ab=
out American workers and made concessions to the unions to end the conflict=
 that had started half a year ago.

This is, to be clear, speculation, and I=E2=80=99m actually skeptical it is=
 true; however, I must warn you, my only counter is somewhat informed specu=
lation of my own. First, there are suspicions that the relentless waves of =
negative stories about TSMC in Arizona may be misinformation from China; th=
ere certainly is a motive, and there have definitely been real challenges, =
but the fact remains the first fab is on pace to open next year, and TSMC h=
as actually increased its commitment to the site. Second, I too have heard =
that Liu left earlier than he planned, but that the reason was unknown.

The reason to even bring this up is that there was a very curious revelatio=
n on the earnings call; every earnings call analysts press TSMC management =
about whether or not they can increase their prices given that companies li=
ke Nvidia are making so much on chips TSMC manufactures. For example, from =
this earnings call:

*I had a question on the AI returns at TSMC. So I think it=E2=80=99s clear =
that AI is producing a large profit pool at your customers. And the HBM is =
also driving super-normal returns for memory players. So my question is, do=
es TSMC believe they=E2=80=99re getting their fair share of the returns in =
the AI value chain today? And is there scope for TSMC to raise pricing for =
AI chips in the future?*

*C.C. Wei:* We always say that we want to sell our value, but it is a conti=
nuous process for TSMC. And let me tell you that we are working on it. We a=
re happy that our customers are doing well. And if customers do well, TSMC =
does well. So let me summarize it. We are working on it, and we hopefully t=
hat we can sell our value.

This has been the refrain for the past few earnings calls, but it is a shif=
t; for example, I previously noted ( https://stratechery.com/2021/tsmc-earn=
ings-semiconductor-economics-and-auto-microcontrollers-tsmcs-advantage/?acc=
ess_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGl=
uZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhe=
nAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0=
ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDIxL3RzbWMtZWFybmluZ3Mtc2VtaWNvbmR1Y3Rvci1lY29ub21pY3MtYW5=
kLWF1dG8tbWljcm9jb250cm9sbGVycy10c21jcy1hZHZhbnRhZ2UvIl19LCJleHAiOjE3MTc2OT=
E4NTEsImlhdCI6MTcxNTA5OTg1MSwiaXNzIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9hcGkucGFzc3BvcnQub25saW5lL=
29hdXRoIiwic2NvcGUiOiJmZWVkOnJlYWQgYXJ0aWNsZTpyZWFkIGFzc2V0OnJlYWQgY2F0ZWdv=
cnk6cmVhZCBlbnRpdGxlbWVudHMiLCJzdWIiOiJSc2V1WUU4amdIZVBwV0pmMWZBYjRDIiwidXN=
lIjoiYWNjZXNzIn0.DtRLu-2hrll8yodZll3e3tn74j1Y9RcKhkQkIK12z04za0YZXBzexK1Pce=
GSxy4WaMfY5Gap16vye-IonuqHb9YbKSGpf2Tw4VWUGNBk-4847QsTRDDnv7gOxQTIaaPev73E1=
T2QG5zuC8eB7p1qUAVGl3b1fEUulVXk8WGqQJFtrkJRaDuDVyeTjoAU6jfG8oFZXejB1qDbmWAl=
p-ARHQI8JmqHz75gxcylnVKLjHfwZfoWJvR2XMenAjCBYJBRjkco-0pSSBLYB-BED-DcNAfxBD1=
HLDY8rWVRu0ioRZOosdYhluEj4t9bhDv_pCIUUG2633sWxW5UToYJONjOuA ) this exchange=
 on the July 2021 earnings call ( https://seekingalpha.com/article/4439360-=
taiwan-semiconductor-manufacturing-company-limiteds-tsm-ceo-c-c-wei-on-q2-2=
021-results ) :

*I want to ask this openly to company management. Does TSMC believe you has=
 acquired the monopoly of the leading edge in the industry, why and why not=
? And if yes, do you think you have the monopoly, why cannot TSMC charge hi=
gher wafer price to cover the increase of CapEx intensity? And lastly, if t=
he company needed to choose between the margin sustainability and also the =
market share, what would be your choice?*

*C.C. Wei:* Charlie, let me answer this question. First, we do have a very =
high market share on the leading-edge technology node. But our pricing stra=
tegy is strategic, and we don=E2=80=99t take an optimistic approach. And it=
=E2=80=99s far away from you say that we try to have bargaining power. In f=
act, we work with our customers closely and we want to help them to be succ=
essful while we get a proper return. That=E2=80=99s all I can answer for yo=
u for our pricing. And looking ahead, we continue our practice, try our bes=
t to hear our customers, to grow and we want to get the proper return. So t=
hat=E2=80=99s why we are firming up our wafer pricing. And we are confident=
 that we can get our gross margin about 50% or above in the long term.

In my Daily Update at the time I spoke fairly complimentarily about TSMC=E2=
=80=99s approach, but since then I have come to view it as a big mistake: t=
he company has had a monopoly on leading edge processes for a decade, and f=
ailed to capitalize on that fact, which means it has left money on the tabl=
e, particularly during the current AI wave. What was notable about this cal=
l is that there seemed to be an acknowledgment of that fact:

*I just wanted to understand gross margin trends. We talked about 3 to 4 pe=
rcentage point gross margin dilution from N3 ramp in second half of the yea=
r. Should we think that the N3-related gross margin drag is more severe tha=
n usual for what we have seen for leading-edge nodes in the past? Or is it =
largely similar to what we have seen in N5 or N7? And when we go to N2, do =
you think that this will kind of be the similar pattern? Or do you think th=
at the gross margin dilution will be lower when we go to like future proces=
s nodes given that N3 seems to be, at least compared to previous cycle, see=
ms to be dragging a little bit more compared to like N5 or N7 in the past f=
ew years?*

*C.C. Wei:* Yes, Gokul, it is true that N3 is taking a longer time to reach=
 the corporate margin than the other nodes like N5 or N7. N5 or N7 before, =
it was like 8 to 10 quarters to reach the corporate. But for N3, we think i=
t will take about 10 to 12 quarters. And this is probably because N3 proces=
s complexity has increased, and also our corporate average gross margin als=
o increased during the period. But another reason is that we set the pricin=
g of N3 very early, several years ahead of production. However, we experien=
ced a lot of cost inflation pressures in the following years. So as a resul=
t, N3 will take a longer time than N5 and N7 to reach the corporate average=
 gross margin. For N2, based on what we can see so far is that we are doing=
 a better job in cost and selling our value, and we expect N2 to have a bet=
ter margin profile than N3.

The key line in there is =E2=80=9Cour corporate average gross margin also i=
ncreased during the period=E2=80=9D; TSMC is no longer targeting 50% gross =
margins, but rather 53%. That, by extension, means that the company priced =
N3 too low (and, to be fair, costs were then further exacerbated by the del=
ays the company experienced with N3). This, to be very clear, was a major m=
anagement mistake. Did it cost Liu his job? I don=E2=80=99t know, but it=E2=
=80=99s certainly a far more plausible explanation if that is indeed what h=
appened.

